JOHANNESBURG – The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has raised South Africa’s growth forecast. It said recent political developments could benefit the economic policy environment. The IMF raised its growth prediction from 0,9 percent to 1,5 percent and 1,7 percent for 2018 and 2019, respectively. The forum says business confidence is likely to firm gradually with the change in the political leadership. READ: World Bank raises SA's 2018 economic growth forecast But the IMF warns that growth prospects remain weighed down by the advancement of the reforms. The IMF has raised concerns about the proposed national minimum wage. It says the policy has the potential to hurt companies’ competitiveness and employment prospects in the formal sector. eNCA